1
00:00:11,208 --> 00:00:14,417
[insects chirping and trilling]

2
00:00:15,917 --> 00:00:18,000
- [tense music playing]
- [Nay Oo pants]

3
00:00:27,167 --> 00:00:28,333
[yelps]

4
00:00:39,167 --> 00:00:41,000
[music fades]

5
00:00:42,083 --> 00:00:43,792
[exhales, sniffles]

6
00:00:48,458 --> 00:00:49,500
[Nay Oo gasps]

7
00:00:50,292 --> 00:00:51,208
[sniffles]

8
00:00:52,417 --> 00:00:55,125
[panting]

9
00:01:00,458 --> 00:01:05,083
[sirens blaring in the distance]

10
00:01:05,167 --> 00:01:08,042
[foreboding music playing]

11
00:01:11,708 --> 00:01:13,000
[whimpers, sobs]

12
00:01:21,833 --> 00:01:23,958
[sirens fade]

13
00:01:26,958 --> 00:01:29,667
[music intensifies]

14
00:01:44,833 --> 00:01:47,583
THE EVIL LAWYER

15
00:01:47,667 --> 00:01:48,958
[music concludes]

16
00:01:51,542 --> 00:01:53,250
[dog barking]

17
00:01:53,333 --> 00:01:54,625
[elevator dings]

18
00:02:01,875 --> 00:02:04,542
[muffled distant chatter]

19
00:02:13,708 --> 00:02:16,500
[soft pensive music playing]

20
00:02:20,250 --> 00:02:22,208
[Ang] The court denied your first bail?

21
00:02:25,583 --> 00:02:28,000
I wanted to see you the day I found out.

22
00:02:29,292 --> 00:02:32,292
But I wasn't sure
if it'd cause you more trouble.

23
00:02:33,375 --> 00:02:36,667
So you didn't visit because
you were afraid I'd be in trouble?

24
00:02:38,292 --> 00:02:39,625
I'm sorry.

25
00:02:43,667 --> 00:02:44,833
[keys jangling]

26
00:02:45,667 --> 00:02:46,833
Come on in.

27
00:02:46,917 --> 00:02:48,000
[lock clicks]

28
00:03:00,208 --> 00:03:02,250
[music fades]

29
00:03:05,917 --> 00:03:06,833
[door closes]

30
00:03:11,625 --> 00:03:13,333
[Mek] You want coffee or anything?

31
00:03:14,083 --> 00:03:15,167
[Ang] Yeah.

32
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:18,458
[coffee pouring]

33
00:03:23,958 --> 00:03:24,833
Oh!

34
00:03:24,917 --> 00:03:26,958
- Don't.
- [Ang] It's fine.

35
00:03:27,042 --> 00:03:29,333
- Let me.
- [Ang] It's okay.

36
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:38,542
[cutlery clattering]

37
00:03:39,292 --> 00:03:41,000
[Ang] When's your next court date?

38
00:03:44,208 --> 00:03:47,208
I don't know. I'm waiting for an update
from my lawyer.

39
00:03:49,417 --> 00:03:51,000
How's Uncle Tom?

40
00:03:53,833 --> 00:03:55,042
He's fine.

41
00:03:56,750 --> 00:03:58,375
But I changed my lawyer…

42
00:03:59,250 --> 00:04:00,542
to Attorney Jittri.

43
00:04:02,500 --> 00:04:04,750
If it wasn't for her,
I'd have died in jail by now.

44
00:04:04,833 --> 00:04:07,000
- But you know that attorney--
- [Mek] I know.

45
00:04:08,250 --> 00:04:09,750
And I've thought it through.

46
00:04:09,833 --> 00:04:12,500
The court charged me
with premeditated murder.

47
00:04:12,583 --> 00:04:15,167
They said it shows intent
that I went to Techin's house.

48
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:21,000
Why did you go to his house?

49
00:04:25,375 --> 00:04:28,042
He said he'd tell me
what you refused to tell me.

50
00:04:30,458 --> 00:04:32,708
The night of the party on the boat.

51
00:04:32,792 --> 00:04:35,625
[soft tense music playing]

52
00:04:43,917 --> 00:04:45,417
What did he tell you?

53
00:04:54,333 --> 00:04:56,542
I'd rather hear it from you.

54
00:05:12,083 --> 00:05:14,167
- [echoing clink]
- [music concludes]

55
00:05:15,833 --> 00:05:18,708
[Ang]<i> That night was a party</i>
<i>for the government coalition.</i>

56
00:05:19,750 --> 00:05:22,458
[gentle string music playing]

57
00:05:25,125 --> 00:05:27,500
[Anan] Sir, this is my son, Techin.

58
00:05:27,583 --> 00:05:28,542
[Techin] Hello, sir.

59
00:05:28,625 --> 00:05:30,375
He's a lawyer now.

60
00:05:30,458 --> 00:05:32,500
[Ang]<i> Uncle Anan was the host</i>
<i>who invited everyone.</i>

61
00:05:32,583 --> 00:05:34,500
Let me know if I can help.

62
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:37,833
[Ang] <i>I went because</i>
<i>I wanted the politicians</i>

63
00:05:37,917 --> 00:05:40,250
<i>to help push the Fisheries Labor</i>
<i>Protection Act</i>

64
00:05:40,333 --> 00:05:43,375
<i>that my team</i>
<i>and the labor coalition drafted together.</i>

65
00:05:43,458 --> 00:05:45,833
<i>Many key government figures were there.</i>

66
00:05:45,917 --> 00:05:47,042
[dark pensive music playing]

67
00:05:47,125 --> 00:05:48,667
[Ang]<i> But Mom said</i>

68
00:05:48,750 --> 00:05:53,292
<i>the most important person to talk to</i>
<i>was Suwat, the Minister of Agriculture.</i>

69
00:05:54,125 --> 00:05:57,833
<i>If he was on board,</i>
<i>the bill was almost sure to pass.</i>

70
00:05:59,583 --> 00:06:01,875
<i>I was fully prepared to present my case.</i>

71
00:06:01,958 --> 00:06:06,292
If fishing is further liberalized,
the problems for laborers will increase.

72
00:06:06,375 --> 00:06:10,833
So, the party will propose
a related bill to protect the welfare…

73
00:06:10,917 --> 00:06:12,000
Suwalee.

74
00:06:12,083 --> 00:06:15,042
[Ang] <i>But I soon realized</i>
<i>this wouldn't work.</i>

75
00:06:16,167 --> 00:06:17,875
<i>Suwat didn't listen to me at all.</i>

76
00:06:18,500 --> 00:06:22,333
<i>There was one waitress at the party</i>
<i>who Suwat seemed to have his eye on.</i>

77
00:06:22,833 --> 00:06:25,458
<i>Suwat was acting like a typical creep.</i>

78
00:06:25,542 --> 00:06:27,333
<i>Nothing too predatory.</i>

79
00:06:27,417 --> 00:06:28,500
Anan.

80
00:06:28,583 --> 00:06:30,208
- How is it?
- Everything's fine.

81
00:06:30,292 --> 00:06:32,208
[Ang]<i> And Uncle Anan was right there.</i>

82
00:06:32,292 --> 00:06:35,000
<i>He surely wouldn't let</i>
<i>anything bad happen on his boat.</i>

83
00:06:37,958 --> 00:06:40,125
[music fades]

84
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:43,667
[Ang] <i>But later that night…</i>

85
00:06:43,750 --> 00:06:44,833
[woman screams]

86
00:06:45,583 --> 00:06:47,542
[Ang]<i> That's when I realized I was wrong.</i>

87
00:06:47,625 --> 00:06:50,208
[Techin] Please continue
to enjoy yourselves.

88
00:06:50,292 --> 00:06:52,750
Someone just got drunk and fell.
It's nothing.

89
00:06:52,833 --> 00:06:55,333
Go on, Top. I'll meet you at the table.

90
00:06:55,417 --> 00:06:57,833
Go get the rest of the liquor. Come on.

91
00:06:57,917 --> 00:06:59,083
Hey, Ang.

92
00:06:59,583 --> 00:07:00,625
It's nothing.

93
00:07:00,708 --> 00:07:02,458
That wasn't the sound of someone falling.

94
00:07:03,667 --> 00:07:05,083
I told you, it's nothing.

95
00:07:05,167 --> 00:07:07,042
[Ang] If it's nothing,
why won't you let me in?

96
00:07:07,125 --> 00:07:08,417
[tense music playing]

97
00:07:08,500 --> 00:07:09,667
Go upstairs.

98
00:07:11,208 --> 00:07:12,375
[Techin] Go.

99
00:07:15,333 --> 00:07:16,292
[clicks tongue]

100
00:07:19,458 --> 00:07:20,958
You asked for it.

101
00:07:27,167 --> 00:07:28,833
[tense music continues]

102
00:07:30,417 --> 00:07:33,250
[Nay Oo sobbing]

103
00:07:35,250 --> 00:07:37,833
[Nay Oo mutters, sobs]

104
00:07:40,458 --> 00:07:41,958
Nee An.

105
00:07:44,458 --> 00:07:45,583
Nee An.

106
00:07:45,667 --> 00:07:47,083
Nee An!

107
00:07:49,167 --> 00:07:50,417
Nee An!

108
00:07:50,917 --> 00:07:54,417
What happened? Mom, let me.

109
00:07:55,625 --> 00:07:57,750
[sobbing]

110
00:07:57,833 --> 00:07:59,708
Please, help my sister!

111
00:08:00,333 --> 00:08:02,208
Please help Nee An!

112
00:08:03,833 --> 00:08:05,083
Nee An!

113
00:08:05,958 --> 00:08:07,500
Ang, that's enough.

114
00:08:08,583 --> 00:08:09,875
Ang!

115
00:08:10,750 --> 00:08:13,250
[shrieking] No! It's not enough!

116
00:08:13,333 --> 00:08:14,542
[sobs]

117
00:08:14,625 --> 00:08:16,833
[in Burmese] Nee An, wake up!

118
00:08:18,250 --> 00:08:20,792
Nee An, wake up!

119
00:08:22,250 --> 00:08:23,292
Nee An!

120
00:08:23,375 --> 00:08:25,125
[in Thai] Why aren't we heading
back to shore?

121
00:08:25,208 --> 00:08:26,583
[sobbing]

122
00:08:33,083 --> 00:08:34,583
[Anan] Who are you calling?

123
00:08:34,667 --> 00:08:35,833
I'm calling for help.

124
00:08:35,917 --> 00:08:37,875
Help with what? The girl's already dead.

125
00:08:37,958 --> 00:08:41,417
[Nay Oo sobbing, muttering]

126
00:08:41,500 --> 00:08:44,292
She's not dead. She could be revived
with the right equipment.

127
00:08:44,375 --> 00:08:47,667
What are the chances? Almost zero.

128
00:08:47,750 --> 00:08:50,917
And have you seen
who else is on this boat?

129
00:08:52,458 --> 00:08:54,708
What? What do you mean?

130
00:08:54,792 --> 00:08:56,708
What does it matter who's on this boat?

131
00:08:56,792 --> 00:08:58,667
No one is doing anything!

132
00:08:58,750 --> 00:09:00,333
Why aren't we heading to shore?

133
00:09:00,417 --> 00:09:02,708
Why isn't anyone doing anything?!

134
00:09:02,792 --> 00:09:06,667
[Nay Oo sobbing]

135
00:09:06,750 --> 00:09:07,917
Mom.

136
00:09:08,542 --> 00:09:09,500
Mom.

137
00:09:12,917 --> 00:09:15,208
Ang, come with me.

138
00:09:17,458 --> 00:09:19,458
[Ang] Mom, where are you taking me?

139
00:09:19,542 --> 00:09:20,708
Mom!

140
00:09:20,792 --> 00:09:22,375
[tense music continues]

141
00:09:23,250 --> 00:09:26,250
Listen to me, Ang.
No one can know about this.

142
00:09:27,875 --> 00:09:29,542
What are you planning to do?

143
00:09:29,625 --> 00:09:31,625
What are you and Uncle Anan
planning to do?

144
00:09:31,708 --> 00:09:35,958
If anyone finds out someone died today,
everyone will be ruined.

145
00:09:36,042 --> 00:09:37,458
[Ang] How could everyone be ruined?

146
00:09:37,542 --> 00:09:40,083
The person who killed her
should be held responsible.

147
00:09:40,167 --> 00:09:41,542
It was Suwat, wasn't it?

148
00:09:41,625 --> 00:09:44,167
I saw him trying to get her drunk
at the table.

149
00:09:44,250 --> 00:09:47,833
[Atchara] Ang, we can't just make
baseless accusations.

150
00:09:48,542 --> 00:09:50,417
No one wanted this to happen.

151
00:09:51,042 --> 00:09:53,042
But if the news gets out…

152
00:09:53,125 --> 00:09:55,958
A man like Suwat won't go down alone.

153
00:09:56,542 --> 00:09:58,167
Everyone in the party will be destroyed.

154
00:09:59,125 --> 00:10:00,417
And what about that girl?

155
00:10:01,875 --> 00:10:04,833
Is her life worth less than
the future of your party?

156
00:10:04,917 --> 00:10:07,000
How can you say that? I'm a doctor.

157
00:10:07,083 --> 00:10:09,500
You saw I did everything I could
to help her.

158
00:10:10,250 --> 00:10:11,833
But that girl overdosed.

159
00:10:12,667 --> 00:10:15,292
We have to protect what we still have.

160
00:10:17,375 --> 00:10:22,042
You want me to sacrifice that girl's life
so you can continue with your work?

161
00:10:22,750 --> 00:10:24,958
- [music concludes]
- She's already dead.

162
00:10:25,042 --> 00:10:27,583
You didn't kill her. I didn't kill her.

163
00:10:28,417 --> 00:10:31,542
But to let this ruin the lives
of everyone on this boat,

164
00:10:31,625 --> 00:10:32,750
what good would that do?

165
00:10:32,833 --> 00:10:36,167
But if we stay quiet,
the guilty one won't be held accountable.

166
00:10:36,250 --> 00:10:38,417
Suwat won't be held
accountable. [sniffles]

167
00:10:38,500 --> 00:10:40,375
[Atchara] We'll hold him accountable.

168
00:10:41,167 --> 00:10:43,125
But not by sending him to prison.

169
00:10:43,208 --> 00:10:44,917
Then what are you going to do?

170
00:10:47,333 --> 00:10:49,292
Use your fisheries bill.

171
00:10:49,917 --> 00:10:53,083
I don't think Suwat can refuse you now.

172
00:10:54,667 --> 00:10:57,583
[dark somber music playing]

173
00:11:26,792 --> 00:11:29,792
[Atchara] <i>If we secure enough seats</i>
<i>in the next election,</i>

174
00:11:32,250 --> 00:11:34,917
<i>at least people like Suwat</i>
<i>and his cronies…</i>

175
00:11:36,833 --> 00:11:39,125
<i>won't be able to do</i>
<i>whatever they want anymore.</i>

176
00:11:43,167 --> 00:11:47,000
[muffled sobbing]

177
00:11:53,875 --> 00:11:56,250
[Atchara] <i>Come and work for my party, Ang.</i>

178
00:11:56,875 --> 00:11:59,708
<i>I promise that the life of the girl</i>
<i>we lost today</i>

179
00:12:00,375 --> 00:12:02,625
<i>will bring change to millions of people.</i>

180
00:12:11,667 --> 00:12:13,250
[Anan muffled] Don't you worry.

181
00:12:14,750 --> 00:12:16,500
You can stop working on the boat.

182
00:12:18,125 --> 00:12:19,833
You can come work at my house.

183
00:12:20,417 --> 00:12:21,667
It'll be much easier.

184
00:12:26,292 --> 00:12:28,042
[Ang trembling]<i> If I could go back,</i>

185
00:12:31,042 --> 00:12:32,958
<i>I never would have let this happen.</i>

186
00:12:33,042 --> 00:12:35,083
[music concludes]

187
00:12:37,417 --> 00:12:38,583
[sniffles]

188
00:12:38,667 --> 00:12:40,750
Even though I didn't kill her…

189
00:12:43,792 --> 00:12:45,375
I just stood there and watched.

190
00:12:47,792 --> 00:12:50,500
I just stood there and watched
her body disappear.

191
00:12:53,375 --> 00:12:55,417
I've become just like them.

192
00:12:57,167 --> 00:12:59,042
I've become the person I hate.

193
00:12:59,125 --> 00:13:00,083
[inhales sharply]

194
00:13:02,792 --> 00:13:04,042
[Mek sighs]

195
00:13:05,708 --> 00:13:07,292
I'm such a piece of shit.

196
00:13:08,792 --> 00:13:10,333
[sobs softly]

197
00:13:11,625 --> 00:13:12,833
Ang.

198
00:13:15,333 --> 00:13:16,208
[sniffles]

199
00:13:16,292 --> 00:13:18,667
The night of the incident
at the golf course,

200
00:13:20,167 --> 00:13:23,083
there was a female caddy from Myanmar
with me and Techin.

201
00:13:23,167 --> 00:13:25,375
Here, let me help you with that.

202
00:13:25,458 --> 00:13:27,125
I'm fine, sir.

203
00:13:27,208 --> 00:13:29,125
[foreboding music playing]

204
00:13:30,375 --> 00:13:33,542
He said that woman was the sister
of the girl who died on the boat.

205
00:13:33,625 --> 00:13:35,417
And she's the one who killed Techin.

206
00:13:38,583 --> 00:13:40,750
Then how did she end up at his house?

207
00:13:43,792 --> 00:13:45,833
I think he was planning on killing her.

208
00:13:46,375 --> 00:13:48,458
I think he wanted to make me an accomplice

209
00:13:48,542 --> 00:13:50,375
so he could blackmail me

210
00:13:50,458 --> 00:13:52,500
into dropping the waste plant fire case.

211
00:13:55,458 --> 00:13:56,500
[sighs softly]

212
00:13:57,000 --> 00:13:58,750
I shouldn't have kept it from you.

213
00:14:00,750 --> 00:14:01,667
[sniffles]

214
00:14:05,500 --> 00:14:07,083
[music fades]

215
00:14:07,750 --> 00:14:08,958
It's okay.

216
00:14:09,583 --> 00:14:12,417
We… We can't change anything now.

217
00:14:13,917 --> 00:14:14,917
Right?

218
00:14:16,083 --> 00:14:17,083
Come here.

219
00:14:19,083 --> 00:14:21,500
[cups clink softly]

220
00:14:24,875 --> 00:14:26,958
[Ang] Where is that woman now?

221
00:14:28,750 --> 00:14:30,000
I don't know.

222
00:14:30,083 --> 00:14:33,458
But there's no evidence
that she even exists.

223
00:14:33,542 --> 00:14:35,292
So everything points back to me.

224
00:14:40,625 --> 00:14:41,958
Mek, let me help you.

225
00:14:47,292 --> 00:14:49,292
I'll help you find that woman.

226
00:14:49,375 --> 00:14:52,292
[suspenseful music playing]

227
00:14:52,375 --> 00:14:54,250
[suspenseful music continues]

228
00:14:59,792 --> 00:15:02,667
[muffled heavy breathing and moans]

229
00:15:04,833 --> 00:15:07,292
[both moan]

230
00:15:08,500 --> 00:15:10,000
[Jittri moans loudly]

231
00:15:12,167 --> 00:15:15,042
- [music builds]
- [both moaning]

232
00:15:16,375 --> 00:15:18,875
- [gasps]
- [music concludes]

233
00:15:19,583 --> 00:15:23,625
[both panting]

234
00:15:29,625 --> 00:15:30,833
[exhales]

235
00:15:39,458 --> 00:15:40,333
Ouch!

236
00:15:40,417 --> 00:15:42,500
[Chanon] When will you stop being so shy?

237
00:15:45,125 --> 00:15:48,083
You have too many secrets.
That's why you won't open up.

238
00:15:51,083 --> 00:15:53,042
The one who's keeping me a secret…

239
00:15:54,583 --> 00:15:57,000
is saying I have too many secrets?

240
00:15:57,083 --> 00:15:58,792
- Seriously?
- [chuckles]

241
00:16:00,208 --> 00:16:01,167
[sighs]

242
00:16:01,833 --> 00:16:04,167
[Jittri] Did you get
the documents I asked for?

243
00:16:05,042 --> 00:16:06,833
That bag. Hand it to me.

244
00:16:18,375 --> 00:16:20,500
The witness list from Anan's side.

245
00:16:22,333 --> 00:16:25,375
But there's one person
who was just added to the list.

246
00:16:25,458 --> 00:16:26,625
Who is it?

247
00:16:26,708 --> 00:16:30,917
This one. His name is Sorn,
a forestry officer.

248
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:33,333
He was the second person
to find Techin's body.

249
00:16:38,833 --> 00:16:41,333
Anan has started sending people
to investigate you.

250
00:16:43,542 --> 00:16:46,750
- You should be careful.
- [soft foreboding music playing]

251
00:16:55,750 --> 00:16:56,958
Why don't you stay the night?

252
00:16:59,375 --> 00:17:00,375
[Jittri] No.

253
00:17:04,042 --> 00:17:06,250
I don't like having someone
sleep next to me.

254
00:17:06,958 --> 00:17:08,125
Unlike you.

255
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:14,333
[door opens]

256
00:17:15,417 --> 00:17:16,292
[door closes]

257
00:17:19,583 --> 00:17:20,583
[grunts softly]

258
00:17:38,292 --> 00:17:39,625
[music fades]

259
00:17:39,708 --> 00:17:42,667
16 SOI MAHANAK 9

260
00:17:45,708 --> 00:17:46,667
[Mek] Uh…

261
00:17:47,167 --> 00:17:49,917
Excuse me, sir. Where is 16 Soi 9?

262
00:17:51,125 --> 00:17:52,375
That way.

263
00:18:00,833 --> 00:18:03,458
[indistinct chatter]

264
00:18:07,583 --> 00:18:09,875
[dog barking in distance]

265
00:18:16,250 --> 00:18:18,292
Uh, excuse me.

266
00:18:19,042 --> 00:18:20,792
Is the Jittri Law Office around here?

267
00:18:20,875 --> 00:18:21,917
Nope.

268
00:18:23,833 --> 00:18:26,750
But it says right here on the card, 16/9.

269
00:18:26,833 --> 00:18:28,375
I said no.

270
00:18:29,917 --> 00:18:33,292
[man 1] Hey, bro. Your shoes are dope.
Where did you get them?

271
00:18:33,375 --> 00:18:35,917
[tense music playing]

272
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:37,542
Thanks.

273
00:18:37,625 --> 00:18:40,125
Hey, you piece of shit!
I asked you a question.

274
00:18:40,958 --> 00:18:41,958
[man 2 jeers]

275
00:18:42,042 --> 00:18:44,333
Not so fast, shirt guy. [laughs]

276
00:18:44,417 --> 00:18:46,667
Relax. Don't be scared.

277
00:18:46,750 --> 00:18:48,125
You're here for Jittri, right?

278
00:18:50,208 --> 00:18:52,667
Actually, I think I have to go now.

279
00:18:52,750 --> 00:18:56,042
Come on, why are you leaving so soon?
Stay with us for a bit.

280
00:18:56,125 --> 00:18:57,542
We're all friends here.

281
00:18:57,625 --> 00:18:59,958
- [music fades]
- Yeah, let's talk first.

282
00:19:00,042 --> 00:19:02,458
Relax. Have a seat.

283
00:19:02,542 --> 00:19:03,875
See? We saved you a spot.

284
00:19:03,958 --> 00:19:06,792
There. All clean. Sit down.

285
00:19:06,875 --> 00:19:07,833
[chuckles]

286
00:19:08,375 --> 00:19:10,625
We're pretty chill in this community.

287
00:19:10,708 --> 00:19:12,417
A lot of people come and go.

288
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:16,708
So I never know who means well
and who doesn't.

289
00:19:16,792 --> 00:19:18,625
- [sniffs]
- [tense music resumes]

290
00:19:19,708 --> 00:19:21,958
If Attorney Jittri really sent for you,

291
00:19:22,042 --> 00:19:23,750
you have to tell me the password.

292
00:19:24,292 --> 00:19:26,208
[music rises]

293
00:19:26,292 --> 00:19:28,500
No, there isn't one. She just told me to…

294
00:19:28,583 --> 00:19:31,292
Wrong. You have two more chances.

295
00:19:33,417 --> 00:19:37,083
If it's cash, I don't have any.
You can take a look.

296
00:19:37,167 --> 00:19:38,750
I'm not carrying any…

297
00:19:38,833 --> 00:19:39,917
- Hey!
- [chair rattles]

298
00:19:44,958 --> 00:19:47,333
This is your last chance, four-eyes.

299
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:49,792
What's the password?!

300
00:19:50,750 --> 00:19:53,375
[music intensifies]

301
00:19:54,500 --> 00:19:55,542
[man 2] Hurry up!

302
00:20:05,417 --> 00:20:07,167
[music builds]

303
00:20:08,208 --> 00:20:09,625
[music falls]

304
00:20:10,375 --> 00:20:11,750
Ten.

305
00:20:15,042 --> 00:20:16,083
Twenty.

306
00:20:19,125 --> 00:20:20,375
Thirty.

307
00:20:27,125 --> 00:20:28,125
Forty.

308
00:20:28,208 --> 00:20:30,042
- I help the poor.
- I help the rich.

309
00:20:30,125 --> 00:20:33,000
- [music stops]
- Help me, I'm stuck in an elevator.

310
00:20:33,917 --> 00:20:35,000
Yeah!

311
00:20:35,083 --> 00:20:38,417
<i>♪ Ten, twenty, thirty, forty!</i>
<i>Come on! Ten, twenty, thirty, forty! ♪</i>

312
00:20:38,500 --> 00:20:40,958
<i>♪ I like to swipe diamonds, swipe gems</i>
<i>Swipe a gold chain ♪</i>

313
00:20:41,042 --> 00:20:43,667
<i>- ♪ I like to pull a zipper! ♪</i>
<i>- ♪ Ten, twenty, thirty, forty! ♪</i>

314
00:20:43,750 --> 00:20:46,417
<i>♪ Come on! Ten, twenty, thirty, forty!</i>
<i>I kick it with a spin ♪</i>

315
00:20:46,500 --> 00:20:49,125
<i>- ♪ With a curve, I do lob shots ♪</i>
<i>- ♪ And chip shots ♪</i>

316
00:20:49,208 --> 00:20:51,583
<i>♪ Ten, twenty, thirty, forty!</i>
<i>Ten, twenty, thirty, forty ♪</i>

317
00:20:51,667 --> 00:20:53,250
<i>♪ Fifty, sixty, seventy, eighty ♪</i>

318
00:20:53,333 --> 00:20:54,333
[man 2] Hey!

319
00:20:54,417 --> 00:20:55,625
The office is this way.

320
00:20:55,708 --> 00:20:59,083
We have a pretty casual style.
It's like an industrial loft. [laughs]

321
00:20:59,167 --> 00:21:01,667
- [mellow music playing]
- [man 2] Come on, hurry up.

322
00:21:02,458 --> 00:21:03,500
Hey, Ma.

323
00:21:03,583 --> 00:21:05,667
Training for a marathon?

324
00:21:05,750 --> 00:21:06,875
- Hello.
- Don't you go running?

325
00:21:06,958 --> 00:21:08,375
- Where are you going?
- The market.

326
00:21:08,458 --> 00:21:10,375
[man 2] To the market. To buy chicken.

327
00:21:10,458 --> 00:21:11,708
She loves that stuff.

328
00:21:12,458 --> 00:21:15,375
Behold! The corridor to the office.

329
00:21:15,458 --> 00:21:17,250
[laughs] Come on.

330
00:21:19,542 --> 00:21:23,833
Please, come in. No password required.

331
00:21:23,917 --> 00:21:26,542
- [chuckles]
- Are you always this much of a dick?

332
00:21:26,625 --> 00:21:29,542
Oh, that depends on the weather.

333
00:21:29,625 --> 00:21:30,833
Mek, my bro.

334
00:21:30,917 --> 00:21:33,208
[laughs]

335
00:21:33,292 --> 00:21:35,458
Asshole. Please, come on in.

336
00:21:37,917 --> 00:21:39,417
- Hello, Auntie
- [woman] Yeah.

337
00:21:39,500 --> 00:21:40,583
[man 2 clears throat]

338
00:21:41,250 --> 00:21:44,042
Welcome. Have you eaten yet?

339
00:21:44,125 --> 00:21:45,500
[music concludes]

340
00:21:46,458 --> 00:21:49,042
Here, have some fried bananas.
I just made them this morning.

341
00:21:49,125 --> 00:21:50,875
[yells] Go wash your hands.

342
00:21:50,958 --> 00:21:54,125
And you! How many times
have I told you to use a glass?

343
00:21:54,208 --> 00:21:56,667
- [man 3] Jeez, Auntie.
- [man 1] You could've just asked nicely…

344
00:21:56,750 --> 00:21:58,583
[woman] Who's going
to want to drink after you?

345
00:21:58,667 --> 00:22:00,000
[man 2] What is it with you?

346
00:22:00,083 --> 00:22:03,042
[overlapping chatter]

347
00:22:03,125 --> 00:22:04,125
[Jittri] Oh.

348
00:22:04,667 --> 00:22:05,875
So you've met them.

349
00:22:05,958 --> 00:22:07,792
This is Kung, my data guy.

350
00:22:07,875 --> 00:22:11,167
The other two are Meuk and Nemo.
They're Kung's assistants.

351
00:22:11,250 --> 00:22:12,500
The sea creature gang?

352
00:22:12,583 --> 00:22:15,667
Oh yeah? What's it to you, mammal?

353
00:22:15,750 --> 00:22:17,292
You're not just my client.

354
00:22:17,375 --> 00:22:19,000
You're going to help me with the cases.

355
00:22:19,083 --> 00:22:21,542
So stop bickering.

356
00:22:22,500 --> 00:22:23,583
It's annoying.

357
00:22:25,417 --> 00:22:27,542
- [Kung] Okay.
- Where's the work I assigned?

358
00:22:28,583 --> 00:22:30,292
[Kung] It's around here somewhere.

359
00:22:31,083 --> 00:22:32,000
One sec.

360
00:22:33,375 --> 00:22:36,250
Here. State-of-the-art technology.

361
00:22:36,333 --> 00:22:38,208
[chuckles]

362
00:22:38,292 --> 00:22:40,792
You've eaten, right?
It's going to be a long day.

363
00:22:40,875 --> 00:22:43,250
Yes, I have. Your mother just asked.

364
00:22:53,375 --> 00:22:54,833
Aunt Noi is my secretary.

365
00:22:56,458 --> 00:22:57,792
Here, take a look.

366
00:22:57,875 --> 00:22:59,333
Your first assignment.

367
00:23:09,042 --> 00:23:10,292
[Mek] A nighttime ordination.

368
00:23:11,250 --> 00:23:13,125
What's the case? A monastic offense?

369
00:23:13,208 --> 00:23:14,792
[foreboding music playing]

370
00:23:14,875 --> 00:23:16,167
Murder.

371
00:23:19,792 --> 00:23:22,875
[crowd cheering over video]

372
00:23:22,958 --> 00:23:26,042
- [crowd cheering]
- [upbeat music playing over speakers]

373
00:23:29,542 --> 00:23:32,833
[Jittri] <i>It happened six months ago</i>
<i>at Sri Don Saeng Temple in Pathum.</i>

374
00:23:32,917 --> 00:23:34,625
[foreboding music continues]

375
00:23:35,292 --> 00:23:39,083
[Jittri]<i> The temple held an ordination</i>
<i>for Nueng, the son of its lay leader.</i>

376
00:23:41,250 --> 00:23:43,417
<i>Over a hundred guests were in attendance.</i>

377
00:23:52,083 --> 00:23:53,333
- [gunshots]
- [music stops]

378
00:23:53,417 --> 00:23:54,750
[crowd screaming]

379
00:23:56,500 --> 00:23:57,417
You bastard, Mai!

380
00:23:57,958 --> 00:23:59,833
- [Jittri] Stop it right there.
- [echoing rumble]

381
00:23:59,917 --> 00:24:02,792
[echoing ringing]

382
00:24:03,792 --> 00:24:05,958
[suspenseful music playing]

383
00:24:06,708 --> 00:24:09,250
[Jittri] This right here
is the prosecution's blind spot.

384
00:24:09,333 --> 00:24:13,000
There's no evidence confirming
the witness actually saw Mai shoot him.

385
00:24:13,083 --> 00:24:17,083
All they have is hearsay that Mai
and the deceased had bad blood.

386
00:24:17,667 --> 00:24:21,417
The key witness who saw Mai
is the victim's friend, a guy named Jeng.

387
00:24:22,667 --> 00:24:25,667
There were so many people there
when it happened.

388
00:24:25,750 --> 00:24:28,667
Between the lights and those speakers…

389
00:24:28,750 --> 00:24:31,417
If you were standing
at a slightly different angle…

390
00:24:33,167 --> 00:24:35,292
you might not have seen the shooter.

391
00:24:35,375 --> 00:24:38,417
If we can confuse the witness
about where they were standing,

392
00:24:38,917 --> 00:24:40,000
we'll win the case.

393
00:24:41,792 --> 00:24:43,833
What? Don't you get it?

394
00:24:43,917 --> 00:24:46,250
If I happen to be in the same place
as my rival

395
00:24:46,333 --> 00:24:48,208
at the same moment he dies,

396
00:24:48,292 --> 00:24:50,083
that doesn't mean I shot him, right?

397
00:24:50,167 --> 00:24:51,083
[scoffs softly]

398
00:24:51,792 --> 00:24:53,958
I knew you'd use a method like this.

399
00:24:55,083 --> 00:24:56,917
- [music fades]
- [echoing whoosh]

400
00:24:57,708 --> 00:24:59,000
What kind of method?

401
00:25:00,917 --> 00:25:02,625
The evidence in this case is weak.

402
00:25:03,167 --> 00:25:05,292
You can't even see Mai's face
in the video.

403
00:25:05,958 --> 00:25:08,458
Even if there were witnesses,
their testimony can't be used.

404
00:25:08,542 --> 00:25:10,917
What you're doing
is confusing the court about the facts.

405
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:12,667
- This way, the guilty--
- Kung.

406
00:25:12,750 --> 00:25:15,458
- [Kung] Yes?
- Right. The facts.

407
00:25:15,542 --> 00:25:17,500
The facts always contain
both lies and truth.

408
00:25:17,583 --> 00:25:20,667
It's the court's job to decide,
not ours. Got it?

409
00:25:20,750 --> 00:25:22,083
- But--
- Look at this.

410
00:25:22,792 --> 00:25:24,417
The witness list in your case.

411
00:25:24,500 --> 00:25:25,958
The one highlighted in yellow.

412
00:25:26,042 --> 00:25:28,083
WITNESS: SORN SAENGRUENGNOP

413
00:25:28,167 --> 00:25:30,750
Sorn Saengruengnop. He's the one I--

414
00:25:30,833 --> 00:25:32,958
The forestry officer
who came to the golf course

415
00:25:33,042 --> 00:25:34,292
when he heard a gunshot.

416
00:25:34,917 --> 00:25:36,875
And he was the second person
to find Techin's body.

417
00:25:36,958 --> 00:25:39,125
- [high-pitched ringing]
- [ominous music playing]

418
00:25:43,042 --> 00:25:46,333
[Jittri] That makes him
the key witness in your case.

419
00:25:49,958 --> 00:25:53,542
Sorn is Mai's father. The defendant
in the ordination ceremony shooting.

420
00:25:55,917 --> 00:25:59,417
So you'll help his son, and in return,
he'll change his testimony in my case?

421
00:25:59,500 --> 00:26:00,542
Hmm?

422
00:26:00,625 --> 00:26:02,333
No. I won't do it.

423
00:26:03,083 --> 00:26:06,083
The only way to win my case
is to find that gun and the Burmese woman.

424
00:26:06,167 --> 00:26:09,083
And how many days,
months or years will that take?

425
00:26:09,167 --> 00:26:11,125
- Please tell me.
- [music concludes]

426
00:26:11,208 --> 00:26:12,458
[sighs]

427
00:26:12,542 --> 00:26:14,542
[Jittri] My source says
Anan's pressuring the court

428
00:26:14,625 --> 00:26:17,125
to move up the date
for the prosecution's witness hearing.

429
00:26:17,208 --> 00:26:19,083
He doesn't want us
to find evidence in time.

430
00:26:19,167 --> 00:26:20,875
He wants your case closed ASAP.

431
00:26:20,958 --> 00:26:22,083
Get it now?

432
00:26:22,167 --> 00:26:24,500
[soft tense music playing]

433
00:26:26,792 --> 00:26:29,583
What we need the most right now is time.

434
00:26:29,667 --> 00:26:31,458
We'll have Sorn buy us that time.

435
00:26:32,083 --> 00:26:34,333
If a key witness like him
suddenly disappears,

436
00:26:34,417 --> 00:26:37,333
the court will have no choice
but to postpone the trial.

437
00:26:44,208 --> 00:26:47,167
Fine. I'll agree to help Mr. Sorn's son.

438
00:26:48,208 --> 00:26:49,625
But I'm not doing it your way.

439
00:26:49,708 --> 00:26:51,167
I'll find my own way.

440
00:26:52,792 --> 00:26:54,083
[papers rustling]

441
00:26:56,208 --> 00:26:57,375
[bag rustling]

442
00:26:59,667 --> 00:27:00,708
[door opens]

443
00:27:02,042 --> 00:27:03,125
[door closes]

444
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:05,250
Hell yeah.

445
00:27:06,917 --> 00:27:09,542
- [birds chirping]
- [music concludes]

446
00:27:14,583 --> 00:27:15,542
[door clunking]

447
00:27:21,625 --> 00:27:22,750
[chains jangling]

448
00:27:30,750 --> 00:27:31,792
[Mek] Hello.

449
00:27:31,875 --> 00:27:33,708
My dad said the new lawyer was a woman.

450
00:27:35,167 --> 00:27:36,375
We're on the same team.

451
00:27:38,542 --> 00:27:39,958
What happened to your face?

452
00:27:41,333 --> 00:27:43,292
Ran into an old rival in here.

453
00:27:47,667 --> 00:27:51,208
So the shooting at the ordination,
was it just because you didn't like him?

454
00:27:53,292 --> 00:27:54,833
I may get into a lot of fights,

455
00:27:54,917 --> 00:27:57,292
but I've never killed someone
over a grudge.

456
00:28:01,875 --> 00:28:04,792
Are you trying to say
you weren't the one who shot him?

457
00:28:05,833 --> 00:28:07,000
I shot him.

458
00:28:07,500 --> 00:28:09,917
But I shot him
because of the shit he pulled.

459
00:28:13,750 --> 00:28:16,042
I already told my old lawyer all this.

460
00:28:16,750 --> 00:28:18,250
But he said it was useless.

461
00:28:20,958 --> 00:28:23,542
Could you tell me again? I want to know.

462
00:28:24,167 --> 00:28:25,750
I'm not like that other lawyer.

463
00:28:30,750 --> 00:28:32,000
[sighs]

464
00:28:37,542 --> 00:28:39,667
[soft tense music playing]

465
00:28:39,750 --> 00:28:40,750
[exhales]

466
00:28:43,625 --> 00:28:45,333
My gang and Nueng's…

467
00:28:47,333 --> 00:28:49,042
we didn't have any beef before.

468
00:28:49,792 --> 00:28:51,792
We just couldn't stand each other.

469
00:28:51,875 --> 00:28:54,042
- We almost threw down a few times.
- [echoing whoosh]

470
00:28:54,125 --> 00:28:56,958
- [crowd cheering]
- [upbeat music playing over speakers]

471
00:29:00,167 --> 00:29:02,625
[overlapping chatter]

472
00:29:03,500 --> 00:29:04,458
[air horn blares]

473
00:29:04,542 --> 00:29:07,292
[Mai] <i>We were just having a water fight</i>
<i>for Songkran.</i>

474
00:29:07,917 --> 00:29:09,375
- [glass shatters]
- [woman screams]

475
00:29:09,458 --> 00:29:11,625
[Mai] <i>Then, suddenly,</i>
<i>his gang came at us.</i>

476
00:29:11,708 --> 00:29:14,417
- [indistinct clamor]
- [thrilling music playing]

477
00:29:18,708 --> 00:29:21,792
[Mai]<i> I punched him,</i>
<i>and he fell back into an ice barrel.</i>

478
00:29:22,458 --> 00:29:24,375
<i>He grabbed a whole block of ice</i>

479
00:29:24,458 --> 00:29:26,583
<i>and threw it right at me.</i>

480
00:29:26,667 --> 00:29:28,708
- [woman shrieks]
- [sounds turns muffled]

481
00:29:32,708 --> 00:29:35,000
[Mai]<i> But it hit my little sister instead.</i>

482
00:29:35,083 --> 00:29:38,292
- [muffled chatter]
- [sorrowful music playing]

483
00:29:46,875 --> 00:29:48,458
[EKG monitor beeping]

484
00:29:48,542 --> 00:29:51,583
[muffled clamor]

485
00:29:55,417 --> 00:29:56,708
[Mai] <i>The doctor said…</i>

486
00:29:58,042 --> 00:30:02,042
<i>my sister had a brain injury.</i>
<i>She was as good as dead.</i>

487
00:30:04,417 --> 00:30:06,250
<i>But the damn cops said</i>

488
00:30:06,333 --> 00:30:08,125
<i>they couldn't charge that bastard.</i>

489
00:30:08,667 --> 00:30:10,000
<i>There was no weapon.</i>

490
00:30:11,875 --> 00:30:15,000
How could there be? It was a block of ice.

491
00:30:18,708 --> 00:30:20,458
So that asshole only got charged…

492
00:30:22,250 --> 00:30:23,833
with simple assault.

493
00:30:24,667 --> 00:30:26,208
<i>But my sister…</i>

494
00:30:27,542 --> 00:30:29,875
<i>- she just kept getting worse…</i>
- [EKG flatlining]

495
00:30:32,708 --> 00:30:34,375
<i>…and eventually passed away.</i>

496
00:30:40,375 --> 00:30:43,208
[muffled sobbing]

497
00:30:48,917 --> 00:30:52,583
<i>So when I found out he was pretending</i>
<i>to be remorseful by getting ordained,</i>

498
00:30:52,667 --> 00:30:54,125
<i>I was even more pissed off.</i>

499
00:30:55,208 --> 00:30:58,208
<i>When you do fucked-up shit,</i>
<i>you've gotta pay for it.</i>

500
00:30:58,292 --> 00:31:00,333
- [gunshot echoing]
- [music concludes]

501
00:31:01,042 --> 00:31:03,125
[Mek] But the maximum penalty
for your crime

502
00:31:03,208 --> 00:31:05,042
is the death penalty.

503
00:31:08,208 --> 00:31:10,542
I have to pay for what I did, too.

504
00:31:10,625 --> 00:31:13,375
[pensive music playing]

505
00:31:17,167 --> 00:31:18,292
[sighs]

506
00:31:22,792 --> 00:31:24,583
Please look after my dad for me.

507
00:31:26,333 --> 00:31:29,375
His daughter's dead,
and his son's in prison.

508
00:31:30,167 --> 00:31:32,000
I'm afraid he won't be able to handle it.

509
00:31:34,750 --> 00:31:36,000
I will.

510
00:31:36,542 --> 00:31:38,833
I'll see what I can do to help.

511
00:31:42,083 --> 00:31:43,333
[phone receiver clatters]

512
00:31:44,958 --> 00:31:46,250
[phone receiver clatters]

513
00:31:50,583 --> 00:31:52,833
- [chains jangling]
- [door opens]

514
00:31:54,292 --> 00:31:56,625
- [door closes]
- [Noi] <i>He killed Mai's sister first.</i>

515
00:31:56,708 --> 00:31:59,042
<i>So Mai acted in a fit of rage.</i>

516
00:31:59,125 --> 00:32:01,792
But Nueng's side will probably deny it…

517
00:32:01,875 --> 00:32:02,917
[door opens]

518
00:32:03,625 --> 00:32:05,083
- Well?
- [music concludes]

519
00:32:05,167 --> 00:32:06,708
Did you find a way?

520
00:32:06,792 --> 00:32:08,917
Mai told me the story about his sister.

521
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:11,708
I think we can use that story
along with his confession.

522
00:32:12,750 --> 00:32:16,208
The court may reduce his sentence by half.
If we're lucky, it'd just be probation.

523
00:32:16,292 --> 00:32:17,792
It's his first offense.

524
00:32:17,875 --> 00:32:20,792
And his motive came from
the loss of a family member.

525
00:32:20,875 --> 00:32:22,625
I think the court might show mercy.

526
00:32:23,708 --> 00:32:27,250
You're going to bet our client's life
on the mercy of the court?

527
00:32:27,333 --> 00:32:29,083
But Mai really did kill someone.

528
00:32:29,167 --> 00:32:31,583
Even with a sympathetic motive,
I think he deserves punishment.

529
00:32:31,667 --> 00:32:33,375
[Jittri] You're not the judge.

530
00:32:33,458 --> 00:32:36,125
It's not your place to decide
who deserves what punishment.

531
00:32:37,625 --> 00:32:39,208
What about the guy who got shot?

532
00:32:39,292 --> 00:32:40,958
Doesn't he deserve justice?

533
00:32:41,042 --> 00:32:42,833
I can't let a murderer walk free.

534
00:32:42,917 --> 00:32:45,167
How dare you call
your own client a murderer?

535
00:32:45,250 --> 00:32:47,792
Let me remind you of something,
in case you forgot.

536
00:32:48,542 --> 00:32:50,958
In court, you and Mai are no different.

537
00:32:51,042 --> 00:32:53,542
If Mai can be a murderer, so can you.

538
00:32:53,625 --> 00:32:56,083
[tense music playing]

539
00:32:56,167 --> 00:32:59,625
- I didn't kill anyone.
- Those are just words. Do you have proof?

540
00:32:59,708 --> 00:33:02,083
You probably think my methods are shitty.

541
00:33:03,000 --> 00:33:06,792
But if the law was applied equally,
there'd be no need for people like me.

542
00:33:07,750 --> 00:33:09,083
Until that day comes,

543
00:33:09,167 --> 00:33:12,333
I'll defend my clients however I want,
and I won't regret it either.

544
00:33:12,417 --> 00:33:15,958
Even after all you've been through,
you still don't get it.

545
00:33:16,042 --> 00:33:18,250
Go back to prison, then.

546
00:33:18,333 --> 00:33:19,667
Stop wasting my time.

547
00:33:22,250 --> 00:33:23,500
Please continue, Aunt Noi.

548
00:33:23,583 --> 00:33:24,875
[Noi] As of right now,

549
00:33:24,958 --> 00:33:28,917
I'd say the witnesses are unreliable.
They were all completely drunk.

550
00:33:30,375 --> 00:33:31,792
[door slams shut]

551
00:33:31,875 --> 00:33:32,875
[Noi] Hmm.

552
00:33:34,208 --> 00:33:35,792
Stubborn, just like his father.

553
00:33:36,917 --> 00:33:38,750
If he keeps seeing the world that way,

554
00:33:38,833 --> 00:33:41,042
there's no way he'll win his own case.

555
00:33:42,000 --> 00:33:43,417
It won't be for long.

556
00:33:47,125 --> 00:33:48,125
[music fades]

557
00:33:48,208 --> 00:33:51,667
RETIREMENT PARTY FOR THE CHIEF JUSTICE
OF THE CRIMINAL COURT

558
00:33:51,750 --> 00:33:55,125
- [overlapping chatter]
- [traditional folk music playing]

559
00:34:02,917 --> 00:34:04,333
[guest greets]

560
00:34:09,667 --> 00:34:10,708
[Padung] Anan.

561
00:34:11,208 --> 00:34:13,167
[Anan] Ah. Padung.

562
00:34:13,250 --> 00:34:14,500
Did you just arrive?

563
00:34:14,583 --> 00:34:16,042
The traffic was terrible.

564
00:34:16,125 --> 00:34:18,458
I almost told my driver to go back home.

565
00:34:19,833 --> 00:34:21,208
You seem to be enjoying the show.

566
00:34:24,583 --> 00:34:27,875
[Anan] "Lady Butsaba Admiring the Shrine."
I like this piece.

567
00:34:27,958 --> 00:34:29,000
[Padung chuckles softly]

568
00:34:29,083 --> 00:34:31,292
I can recite
volumes of Supreme Court rulings,

569
00:34:31,375 --> 00:34:34,458
but when it comes to art,
music, or literature,

570
00:34:34,542 --> 00:34:36,250
it all goes right over my head.

571
00:34:37,167 --> 00:34:39,125
[Anan] It's from the story of Inao.

572
00:34:40,208 --> 00:34:42,167
After winning the war,

573
00:34:42,250 --> 00:34:46,250
Princess Butsaba comes out
to admire the beauty of the shrine.

574
00:34:49,250 --> 00:34:51,542
But our Butsaba

575
00:34:51,625 --> 00:34:54,625
won't be coming out to dance
anytime soon, will she?

576
00:34:55,583 --> 00:34:57,500
[music concludes]

577
00:34:57,583 --> 00:34:59,458
[guests applauding]

578
00:35:02,083 --> 00:35:03,583
I really don't understand.

579
00:35:03,667 --> 00:35:05,792
Why is a simple waste plant fire case

580
00:35:05,875 --> 00:35:08,000
taking so long to wrap up?

581
00:35:09,542 --> 00:35:11,542
Troublemakers just keep popping up.

582
00:35:12,292 --> 00:35:13,292
Who?

583
00:35:13,375 --> 00:35:18,000
[host] At this time,
I'd like to invite Judge Rit Piriyawich,

584
00:35:18,083 --> 00:35:20,500
as a representative for all of us

585
00:35:20,583 --> 00:35:23,333
to honor us with a few words.
Please put your hands together.

586
00:35:23,417 --> 00:35:26,417
[guests applauding]

587
00:35:27,750 --> 00:35:32,375
The Chief Justice taught me
from my very first day as a judge that…

588
00:35:33,333 --> 00:35:35,292
being a judge

589
00:35:36,292 --> 00:35:38,958
isn't just a nine-to-five job.

590
00:35:39,042 --> 00:35:40,292
[foreboding music playing]

591
00:35:40,375 --> 00:35:43,667
[Rit] You must also conduct yourself
with integrity at all times.

592
00:35:43,750 --> 00:35:46,042
It is a difficult and heavy burden

593
00:35:47,292 --> 00:35:49,625
that can lead to bias

594
00:35:49,708 --> 00:35:51,542
in your rulings.

595
00:35:52,792 --> 00:35:56,292
- There was a time…
- I'm doing my best to speed it up.

596
00:35:57,375 --> 00:36:00,542
But Rit exercised his right
to be a co-judge.

597
00:36:01,333 --> 00:36:04,500
If I rush it any more,
it'll look suspicious.

598
00:36:07,167 --> 00:36:09,375
I managed to get Mek out of the way…

599
00:36:09,458 --> 00:36:11,542
…no matter how immense,

600
00:36:12,667 --> 00:36:15,708
we must not waver

601
00:36:15,792 --> 00:36:17,958
in the face of pressure,

602
00:36:18,042 --> 00:36:19,917
in the face of fear,

603
00:36:20,000 --> 00:36:22,833
or in the face of our own inner biases.

604
00:36:23,833 --> 00:36:25,792
We must not allow these things

605
00:36:25,875 --> 00:36:28,208
to undermine us

606
00:36:28,833 --> 00:36:31,792
and the sacred judicial institution

607
00:36:31,875 --> 00:36:34,583
that we are sworn to uphold.

608
00:36:34,667 --> 00:36:35,833
Thank you very much.

609
00:36:35,917 --> 00:36:38,000
[guests applauding]

610
00:36:41,417 --> 00:36:43,167
Normally, I'm a patient man.

611
00:36:43,250 --> 00:36:44,542
[music concludes]

612
00:36:46,125 --> 00:36:49,375
So if I feel that it's slow,

613
00:36:50,375 --> 00:36:53,500
it must be taking way too long.

614
00:36:53,583 --> 00:36:55,750
[tense music playing]

615
00:36:56,417 --> 00:36:58,042
Don't make me warn you again.

616
00:36:59,875 --> 00:37:03,125
Not everyone is as patient as I am.

617
00:37:07,792 --> 00:37:09,667
[music intensifies]

618
00:37:14,083 --> 00:37:15,083
[sighs]

619
00:37:18,708 --> 00:37:20,875
[music concludes]

620
00:37:23,583 --> 00:37:30,333
WITNESS HEARING:
THE ORDINATION CEREMONY SHOOTING CASE

621
00:37:30,417 --> 00:37:32,917
[indistinct chatter]

622
00:37:42,708 --> 00:37:45,375
Tell me. What's our strategy?

623
00:37:49,500 --> 00:37:51,458
I'm only agreeing to do this one case.

624
00:37:54,542 --> 00:37:55,625
Listen,

625
00:37:56,417 --> 00:37:59,208
to win a case where we're the accused,

626
00:37:59,292 --> 00:38:01,458
it's not about what we say
to convince the court.

627
00:38:01,542 --> 00:38:05,750
Because being accused
is the same as being branded a bad person.

628
00:38:07,250 --> 00:38:09,875
And bad people don't tell the truth.

629
00:38:13,958 --> 00:38:16,333
[echoing jangle]

630
00:38:18,792 --> 00:38:21,750
[intriguing music playing]

631
00:38:21,833 --> 00:38:23,875
[Jittri echoing]
<i>The only chance to win this case</i>

632
00:38:23,958 --> 00:38:26,583
<i>is to destroy</i>
<i>the other side's credibility.</i>

633
00:38:35,125 --> 00:38:38,833
<i>Make it seem as if</i>
<i>the prosecution is the one who's lying.</i>

634
00:38:40,375 --> 00:38:42,542
[music rises]

635
00:38:59,500 --> 00:39:02,458
[Jittri] <i>Once you make the prosecution</i>
<i>lose all credibility,</i>

636
00:39:03,792 --> 00:39:06,625
<i>then no matter how firmly</i>
<i>the eyewitness testifies,</i>

637
00:39:08,125 --> 00:39:11,750
<i>there's a chance the court</i>
<i>won't give their testimony any weight.</i>

638
00:39:35,333 --> 00:39:37,125
[music fades]

639
00:39:43,375 --> 00:39:46,875
- You were close to the deceased, correct?
- Yes.

640
00:39:46,958 --> 00:39:49,625
We grew up together.
Our families know each other.

641
00:39:51,000 --> 00:39:54,292
On that day, did you know
that a shooting was going to happen?

642
00:39:54,917 --> 00:39:56,375
How would I know that?

643
00:39:57,125 --> 00:39:59,333
If I knew, would my friend be dead?

644
00:39:59,417 --> 00:40:02,833
And before the incident,
did you see the defendant at the event?

645
00:40:04,583 --> 00:40:05,833
[Jeng] I didn't see him.

646
00:40:06,333 --> 00:40:09,583
But if I had,
I would have stomped him to death.

647
00:40:09,667 --> 00:40:10,833
[lawyer clears throat]

648
00:40:12,333 --> 00:40:14,708
I mean, I would have taught him a lesson.

649
00:40:18,667 --> 00:40:20,750
You said you were close with the deceased.

650
00:40:20,833 --> 00:40:22,167
Were you previously aware

651
00:40:22,250 --> 00:40:24,875
that the deceased had conflicts
with people other than the defendant?

652
00:40:24,958 --> 00:40:27,875
I wouldn't know. The conflict
I did know about was with that guy, Mai.

653
00:40:27,958 --> 00:40:29,500
So you had no prior knowledge

654
00:40:29,583 --> 00:40:31,875
that more than ten separate police reports
had been filed

655
00:40:31,958 --> 00:40:34,292
against the deceased
for violence involving others.

656
00:40:34,375 --> 00:40:36,708
- And among those cases--
- [lawyer] Pardon me, Your Honor.

657
00:40:36,792 --> 00:40:40,500
I believe the deceased's conflicts
with others are irrelevant to this case.

658
00:40:42,792 --> 00:40:44,625
[judge] Keep it relevant, Counselor.

659
00:40:52,875 --> 00:40:54,708
[Mek] Document L.7, Your Honor.

660
00:41:00,792 --> 00:41:04,417
This is where you stood
when you saw the shooting, is that right?

661
00:41:05,667 --> 00:41:06,667
[Jeng] Yeah.

662
00:41:06,750 --> 00:41:08,708
MAP OF THE DAY OF THE INCIDENT

663
00:41:08,792 --> 00:41:10,417
Are you sure? Take a closer look.

664
00:41:13,292 --> 00:41:14,417
I'm sure.

665
00:41:14,500 --> 00:41:16,833
I remember a utility pole
was on my right.

666
00:41:17,333 --> 00:41:21,250
I stood there with Gas and Khun.
You can go ask them.

667
00:41:23,417 --> 00:41:26,500
[Mek] And this is the spot
where the defendant was standing, right?

668
00:41:27,208 --> 00:41:29,958
[Jeng] Yeah, he was under the teak tree.

669
00:41:30,042 --> 00:41:31,208
He was running away.

670
00:41:31,292 --> 00:41:34,167
Are you sure about that?
Because it was very dark under that tree.

671
00:41:34,250 --> 00:41:37,083
How could it be dark?
The whole party was lit up.

672
00:41:37,917 --> 00:41:41,167
Oh, and another thing,
when that guy Mai fired…

673
00:41:41,250 --> 00:41:43,958
the muzzle flash was bright.

674
00:41:44,042 --> 00:41:45,417
His face was pretty damn clear.

675
00:41:47,792 --> 00:41:49,583
[soft tense music playing]

676
00:41:49,667 --> 00:41:51,500
But you previously gave a statement

677
00:41:51,583 --> 00:41:54,125
that you turned around
after you heard the gunshot.

678
00:41:54,708 --> 00:41:56,208
It went "bang," then I turned.

679
00:41:56,292 --> 00:41:58,917
Then how could you have seen
the muzzle flash?

680
00:42:00,208 --> 00:42:04,667
So, did you see the defendant
while he was shooting or afterwards?

681
00:42:05,667 --> 00:42:07,875
I turned just before he fired the shot.

682
00:42:09,292 --> 00:42:12,500
So, to be clear,
you didn't duck or even blink

683
00:42:12,583 --> 00:42:13,667
like everyone else?

684
00:42:13,750 --> 00:42:15,708
Then how did you still see the flash?

685
00:42:17,125 --> 00:42:19,583
I've shot guns before. I'm not afraid.

686
00:42:19,667 --> 00:42:20,958
Why are you asking? Seriously.

687
00:42:21,042 --> 00:42:22,833
[lawyer] Objection, Your Honor.

688
00:42:22,917 --> 00:42:25,167
I believe he's pressuring the witness.

689
00:42:26,958 --> 00:42:29,125
[judge] Don't pressure
the witness, Counsel.

690
00:42:29,875 --> 00:42:31,083
Proceed.

691
00:42:34,083 --> 00:42:35,208
Yes, Your Honor.

692
00:42:35,292 --> 00:42:37,542
Then could you please confirm
one more time

693
00:42:37,625 --> 00:42:40,667
that the blue dot marks the spot
where you were standing?

694
00:42:41,167 --> 00:42:43,708
Confirm that it matches
the blue dot on the screen.

695
00:42:45,250 --> 00:42:46,875
Yeah. I was standing right there.

696
00:42:46,958 --> 00:42:49,792
And do you remember
there were speakers there that night?

697
00:42:52,958 --> 00:42:55,458
There was music. So yeah,
there were speakers. I remember.

698
00:42:55,542 --> 00:42:57,417
[Mek] Do you remember
where they were?

699
00:42:58,500 --> 00:42:59,792
I wouldn't know.

700
00:43:02,208 --> 00:43:05,083
[Mek] Your Honor, I request permission
to show the witness a video clip,

701
00:43:05,167 --> 00:43:06,583
to aid in his testimony.

702
00:43:10,542 --> 00:43:12,833
[foreboding music playing]

703
00:43:24,667 --> 00:43:27,125
[Mek] That's the spot where you said
you were standing, correct?

704
00:43:27,208 --> 00:43:30,375
And that's where you said
the defendant committed the act.

705
00:43:35,167 --> 00:43:38,375
Do you see the large set of speakers
blocking your line of sight?

706
00:43:39,625 --> 00:43:41,125
You don't remember that at all?

707
00:43:42,750 --> 00:43:44,417
They were just there, that's all.

708
00:43:45,875 --> 00:43:48,417
But what I saw for sure was Mai's face.

709
00:43:48,500 --> 00:43:49,750
It was so damn clear.

710
00:43:54,542 --> 00:43:56,208
[Mek] This is my last question.

711
00:43:57,333 --> 00:44:00,417
Did you drink any alcohol that night?

712
00:44:02,833 --> 00:44:03,833
No.

713
00:44:04,417 --> 00:44:05,917
I didn't drink. [sniffs]

714
00:44:10,458 --> 00:44:12,042
He claims he wasn't drinking.

715
00:44:13,042 --> 00:44:14,458
[Mek] No further questions.

716
00:44:17,792 --> 00:44:20,958
Prosecutor, any redirect?

717
00:44:21,042 --> 00:44:22,250
[lawyer] No, Your Honor.

718
00:44:31,833 --> 00:44:33,250
[judge] Witness, you may step down.

719
00:44:35,833 --> 00:44:37,000
[music fades]

720
00:44:37,083 --> 00:44:39,125
I'd like to call my next witness.

721
00:44:39,208 --> 00:44:41,792
Mr. Mana Saengsom, known as Abhinanto.

722
00:44:41,875 --> 00:44:43,583
The abbot of Pa Ban Khru Temple.

723
00:44:45,917 --> 00:44:48,833
[intriguing music playing]

724
00:45:19,250 --> 00:45:21,083
I hereby swear before the Emerald Buddha…

725
00:45:21,167 --> 00:45:23,458
- One moment, please.
- [music stops]

726
00:45:23,542 --> 00:45:25,708
A monk is not required to swear an oath.

727
00:45:26,917 --> 00:45:28,917
Prosecutor, you may proceed.

728
00:45:35,583 --> 00:45:38,583
On the night of the incident,
where were you?

729
00:45:38,667 --> 00:45:41,083
And what did you witness?
Could you please tell us?

730
00:45:41,167 --> 00:45:44,000
At that time, uh…

731
00:45:44,583 --> 00:45:46,708
They were holding
an ordination procession outside.

732
00:45:46,792 --> 00:45:48,417
I was inside the prayer hall.

733
00:45:49,042 --> 00:45:50,125
[gunshots]

734
00:45:50,208 --> 00:45:51,625
[crowd screaming]

735
00:45:51,708 --> 00:45:55,083
[Mana]<i> I heard gunshots</i>
<i>and people screaming.</i>

736
00:45:55,167 --> 00:45:57,917
- [running footsteps]
- [suspenseful music playing]

737
00:45:59,083 --> 00:46:01,042
[Mana] <i>I saw Mai.</i>

738
00:46:01,125 --> 00:46:04,833
<i>He ran to a motorcycle</i>
<i>parked next to the prayer hall.</i>

739
00:46:07,167 --> 00:46:09,000
How clearly did you see his face?

740
00:46:10,792 --> 00:46:12,000
[motorcycle engine revs]

741
00:46:12,667 --> 00:46:13,708
[Mana] <i>Very clearly.</i>

742
00:46:13,792 --> 00:46:17,875
<i>We even made eye contact</i>
<i>before he rode off.</i>

743
00:46:19,208 --> 00:46:22,333
I am only speaking the truth.

744
00:46:23,833 --> 00:46:27,333
Lying is a sin.

745
00:46:27,417 --> 00:46:28,792
That's enough, Father.

746
00:46:29,625 --> 00:46:30,708
No further questions.

747
00:46:33,333 --> 00:46:35,625
The defense may cross-examine.

748
00:46:44,625 --> 00:46:46,042
[music fades]

749
00:46:46,125 --> 00:46:48,292
You knew the deceased, is that correct?

750
00:46:48,375 --> 00:46:51,083
[Mana] Yes. He was a good boy.

751
00:46:51,167 --> 00:46:53,958
He could be a bit unruly at times.

752
00:46:54,042 --> 00:46:57,417
But he was ordained as a novice under me
when he was a boy.

753
00:46:58,250 --> 00:47:00,583
[Mek] Do you know
the boys sitting over there?

754
00:47:03,000 --> 00:47:04,750
Yes, I know all of them.

755
00:47:05,292 --> 00:47:08,667
They've been running around the temple
since they were children.

756
00:47:08,750 --> 00:47:10,375
Some of them were even ordained.

757
00:47:10,458 --> 00:47:12,417
So, I definitely know them.

758
00:47:13,125 --> 00:47:16,417
Especially Jeng, Nueng, and Mai.

759
00:47:16,500 --> 00:47:18,042
They were the ringleaders.

760
00:47:18,125 --> 00:47:22,500
So, for me to be here as a witness…

761
00:47:22,583 --> 00:47:25,667
I will speak without any bias.

762
00:47:25,750 --> 00:47:27,750
[intriguing music playing]

763
00:47:29,917 --> 00:47:31,667
Holding an ordination ceremony at night,

764
00:47:31,750 --> 00:47:33,958
with liquor, lights and music
like a nightclub.

765
00:47:34,042 --> 00:47:36,250
Is that considered normal in Buddhism?

766
00:47:36,333 --> 00:47:38,250
[Mana] It may seem strange to you.

767
00:47:38,333 --> 00:47:41,833
But the truth is,
some people aren't free during the day.

768
00:47:41,917 --> 00:47:44,125
So they ask their relatives and friends

769
00:47:44,208 --> 00:47:46,375
to come help out at night.

770
00:47:46,458 --> 00:47:47,583
But inside the prayer hall,

771
00:47:47,667 --> 00:47:52,625
everything followed religious tradition
without any changes.

772
00:47:55,292 --> 00:47:57,875
So does that mean anyone can hold
an ordination at night?

773
00:47:57,958 --> 00:48:00,542
I thought it would have to be someone
who is close to you,

774
00:48:00,625 --> 00:48:02,625
or someone who donates a lot
to the temple.

775
00:48:02,708 --> 00:48:05,625
That's not necessary.
One can be ordained without money.

776
00:48:05,708 --> 00:48:07,375
There's no need to worry about that.

777
00:48:07,458 --> 00:48:09,458
Because Buddhism is open to all.

778
00:48:09,542 --> 00:48:12,167
If the poor wish to be ordained and study,

779
00:48:12,250 --> 00:48:14,167
the temple will ordain them.

780
00:48:15,792 --> 00:48:17,667
[music fades]

781
00:48:30,542 --> 00:48:34,125
Well, Counselor?
Do you have any further questions?

782
00:48:35,583 --> 00:48:36,625
[sighs]

783
00:48:37,292 --> 00:48:38,958
No further questions, Your Honor.

784
00:48:50,167 --> 00:48:52,542
[judge] Then let's examine
the defendant's witnesses.

785
00:48:52,625 --> 00:48:53,833
So as not to waste time.

786
00:48:53,917 --> 00:48:55,292
Yes, Your Honor.

787
00:48:55,375 --> 00:48:58,125
However, the defense would like to submit
an additional witness list.

788
00:48:58,208 --> 00:49:00,250
[tense music playing]

789
00:49:05,917 --> 00:49:07,458
Objection, Your Honor.

790
00:49:07,542 --> 00:49:10,875
The defense cannot submit
an additional witness list at this time.

791
00:49:10,958 --> 00:49:12,542
It's a violation of trial procedure.

792
00:49:13,667 --> 00:49:15,875
But I have new information, Your Honor.

793
00:49:15,958 --> 00:49:18,667
These three witnesses will confirm

794
00:49:18,750 --> 00:49:22,750
the defendant could not possibly have
murdered the deceased.

795
00:49:22,833 --> 00:49:26,250
[crowd gasping, chattering]

796
00:49:26,333 --> 00:49:29,042
[Jittri] I request permission to call
all three witnesses to the stand.

797
00:49:29,125 --> 00:49:31,833
[echoing rumble]

798
00:49:33,208 --> 00:49:35,958
- [door creaks]
- [footsteps echoing]

799
00:49:37,125 --> 00:49:40,000
[tense dramatic music playing]

800
00:49:46,583 --> 00:49:49,125
[Jittri] Mr. Somchai, the Mayor.

801
00:49:49,958 --> 00:49:52,417
Mr. Sirikorn, the Chief of Forestry.

802
00:49:52,500 --> 00:49:55,625
And Mr. Tawanchai, the School Director.

803
00:50:00,583 --> 00:50:01,500
[music fades]

804
00:50:01,583 --> 00:50:04,542
All three were with the defendant
the entire night.

805
00:50:04,625 --> 00:50:09,375
And that night, the defendant
never set foot inside the temple.

806
00:50:10,500 --> 00:50:12,917
[intense dramatic music playing]

807
00:50:17,125 --> 00:50:19,375
False speech.

808
00:50:19,458 --> 00:50:20,667
<i>Sathu.</i>

809
00:50:20,750 --> 00:50:22,167
[music concludes]

810
00:50:23,750 --> 00:50:26,542
[dark intriguing music playing]

811
00:51:43,625 --> 00:51:46,250
[dark tense music playing]

812
00:52:43,667 --> 00:52:45,208
[music concludes]
